# Private Share — Project Decisions

## Security Model

- **End-to-end encryption**: All secret content and files are encrypted client-side (AES-256-GCM, PBKDF2 key derivation) before reaching the server. The server stores only ciphertext.
- **Zero-knowledge**: The server must never be able to recover or read secrets, text or files. Encryption keys exist only in the URL fragment (`#key`) which is never sent to the server.
- **Burn after reading**: Secrets are permanently deleted after a single retrieval. Files are deleted after a single download.
- **Password protection**: When enabled, passwords are bcrypt-hashed server-side. Wrong password attempts must not delete or reveal the secret.
- **No sensitive data in logs**: Logs must never contain secret content, encryption keys, plaintext passwords, or file contents. Audit only IDs, timestamps, and IP addresses.

## Architecture

- **React 19 + Inertia v2 + TypeScript**: Frontend uses React components served via Inertia.js. All frontend code lives in `resources/js/`.
- **Atomic Design**: Components organized as atoms → molecules → organisms → layouts → pages (`resources/js/components/{atoms,molecules,organisms,layouts}/` and `resources/js/Pages/`).
- **Dedicated logic files**: Business logic separated from React components into services (`resources/js/services/`), hooks (`resources/js/hooks/`), and libraries (`resources/js/lib/`). The crypto module (`lib/crypto.ts`) handles all E2E encryption primitives, and services orchestrate flows (secret sharing, secret viewing, file upload/download, markdown).
- **Controller-based routing**: Standard Laravel controllers and `routes/web.php` — no Folio.
- **Feature flags (independent)**: Two independent Pennant feature flags — `Authentication` (Google SSO, guest links, profile menu) and `FileUploads` (chunked encrypted uploads). Controlled via `FEATURE_AUTH` and `FEATURE_FILE_UPLOADS` env vars. People can fork and toggle them independently.
- **Chunked file uploads**: Large files are split into 8 MB chunks, each encrypted individually with a derived chunk IV, uploaded via a three-step API (initiate → chunk → complete).
- **Branding**: Colors, logo, and container style are configurable via `config/branding.php` and CSS custom properties (`--brand-primary`, `--brand-secondary`, `--brand-accent`).
- **Shared props via Inertia middleware**: `HandleInertiaRequests` middleware shares `auth`, `branding`, `features`, `appName`, `helpText`, `debug`, and `flash` to all pages.
- **"How it works" modal**: Centralized help lives in `HowItWorksModal`. It is reachable from the profile dropdown when `Authentication` is enabled, otherwise from a standalone info button in the topbar. An optional support line at the bottom of the modal is configurable via `SUPPORT_HELP_TEXT` (read in `config/support.php`, exposed as the `helpText` shared prop); when empty, no help section renders.
- **Error pages**: In production, every error response (any 4xx/5xx) renders the branded `Error` React component via Inertia — nothing falls through to the default framework page. Locally, only predictable user-facing codes (403, 404, 419, 429, 503) are styled so Laravel's debug page stays available for unexpected errors. JSON API requests bypass Inertia and return standard Laravel error responses. Redirects and successful responses are never converted to error pages, and only intentional `abort()` (HttpException) messages are surfaced to the client — raw exception messages are never leaked.
